commits.commitMessage:
Workaround file descriptor table corruption

Calling iks_GetKey() appears to corrupt the file descriptor table
for some reason.  Observed symptom is all future calls to qapi_FS calls
will fail with QAPI_ERR_EBADF.  Work-around by closing and reopening
key file around call to iks_GetKey().

Resolves: ATSWI-394
Change-Id: Icbfd029870eaccb06dfda02ca11bd5e1f6b21778
commits.subject: Workaround file descriptor table corruption

comments.message:
It isn't great to have this seek "fix", because we're not really sure how it fixes things, but until we have a better solution I'm okay to add this. Also not keen on the CONFIG flag be called RTOS, I'd prefer something more like "KLUDGES_TO_MAKE_THINGS_WORK" :).

I can +2 this, if we do not think we are going to get any answers to the real cause.

commits.commitMessage:
Correct recovery of iotkeys file after invalid key.

If an invalid key is detected when loading the iotkeys file, make
sure the entire file is deleted.  Otherwise new keys will just
be added on to the end of the invalid key file, causing every
subsequent load of the file to fail as well.

Resolves: ATSWI-380
Change-Id: I716361d66dfd69f9c60c925e9600a2519edbc186
(cherry picked from commit eeeb446b96c931eb13817fc3f12aee9ffcfcb189)
commits.subject: Correct recovery of iotkeys file after invalid key.

commits.commitMessage:
Bypass configtree when using secStore on hl78

This patch de-couples secStore from le_cfg. Instead of going through
congiftree to store credentials/key material, secStore now creates and
manages it's own file.

Resolves: LE-16488
Change-Id: I64fdc29e6c6e2709c4f3f2550899bf68d106a4b0
commits.subject: Bypass configtree when using secStore on hl78

comments.message: Can be done as two uint16_t's
Set this to whatever the maximum anticipated number of secStore credentials is.
Investigate: Can we modify this to make it portable across all platforms (linux, threadx, freerots) i.e. by using le_fs, configtree, etc... instead of C-style FILE API?

commits.commitMessage:
Make secure storage backwards compatible

Currently, secure storage determines which TZ to use based off the build time flags. However, if the device does not support the specified TZ, the secure storage will assert and fail. This change will also check at runtime whether the specific build flags are applicable. If not, it will fallback to the working version.

Resolves: LE-16386
Change-Id: I523f88bbf7c5a7e112985f9e8a048c1e87d19912
commits.subject: Make secure storage backwards compatible

comments.message: should remove this #else and move it below otherwise other products will be using TZ
Patch test passed (re-Bootstrap from those 4 Legato vs. FW combinations, plus IKS regression on IKS/TZ4 case) - see LETEST-6898

commits.commitMessage:
Adds simplified IKS-based SecStore

IKS-based secStore that uses a single IKS key to encrypy/decrypt
all entries in SecStore.

Resolves: LE-16043
Change-Id: I8a9a094c6027947b54e3933cfe3e508dfa2eff1f
commits.subject: Adds simplified IKS-based SecStore

comments.message: Adding myself to coordinate HL78 IS
Looks fine to me on first pass, although I'm not too familiar with IKS.
Write to 0 of buffer's that ever have plain text
I think it makes more sense to use IKS_MAX_PACKET_SIZE instead.

The way GenerateKey is being called from GetKeyRef below means that a duplicate here should not happen but if it does then it should be an error as the keyRefPtr is likely not set.

Since GenerateKey is only being called in one place maybe this code can just be part of the GetKeyRef function.
Done. Moved it to within GetKeyRef
May want to make keyRef a file scope variable and just call GetKeyRef once on initialization to reduce the calls to iks.
I did this intentionally as I thought it would be more secure if it's retained just on the stack. Will move to a static within the file
Somewhere in the upper layer, the secure storage app should make sure to zerorize this buffer to help prevent leaking the client data.
I tried doing as you suggested in SecStore but it would break the const. I could cast it if that's a better alternative

To clarify, I'm suggesting that the SecStore app zerorize the buffer after it calls pa_secStore_Write, so not in this function.  This is assuming that the SecStore app no longer needs the data after it calls this function.  Perhaps this is something that should be handled by the RPC code automatically.
Somewhere in the upper layer, the secure storage app should make sure to zerorize this buffer to help prevent leaking the client data.
Not as clear on the read side when I should zeroize the buffer
The read buffer should be zerorized after the data has been sent to the client because it is no needed after that.  Again, perhaps this is something that should be handled by the RPC code.
We discussed adding some kind of #define MAX_KEY (MAX_ENCRYPTED_DATA_BYTES - MAX_ENCRYPTION_OVERHEAD)

Migrate SecStore data from TZ-based to IKS-based system.

1) Introduce secStore versioning.

needed, and the exact migration path (version1 -> version2)
3) Read-decrypt-encrypt-write the data using different keys
(TZ and IKS)

commits.subject: Migrate SecStore data from TZ-based to IKS-based system.

comments.message:
Hi Stan
The code mostly looks okay to me. Have few questions. 
Recommendation:
Since the upgrade/downgrade is an important and sensitive area for the customers, I'd suggest to be elaborate on the unit tests performed. I think it will be better if you could list on the ticket all the unit tests with results including all edge conditions/corner cases tested.
Maximum keys 8 (reduced from 100) is enough? How did you decide on the number?

In bare-bones Legato, there are only 2 keys ("avc" and "user"). Each new customer app, will add one more key. So in 90+% real-world cases, it will be not more than 3-5 keys in the system in total.
Even if actual number of keys exceeds 8, the hashmap will still work fine; lookup time may increase slightly due to extra linked-list walks.

This is all for the sake of memory optimization. Currently, initializing a hashmap with 100 causes allocation of 256 buckets 12 bytes each... so switching to smaller size allows to save more than 2K of memory right away.
Recovering or deleting the keys file?
It's recovery mechanism, works by deleting and re-creating keys file... I'll make this message more clear.
I might have missed this case. But what happens if user tries to downgrade from IKS to SFS version? Or this patch is only for upgrade scenario? Please explain.

Yes, the patch is only for upgrade scenario.
Current Legato code can't use SFS as a primary mechanism for Secure Storage, because it supports only TZ/IKS/ConfigTree design. On lines 176-180, one can see that the current "secstore version" can only be TZ or IKS, but not SFS. 

To switch back to SFS, you'd need to downgrade to let's say 18.10, and this code won't be relevant anymore.

10 of 11 test cases passed, each set is tested on:
A) 19.11.4 -> Master
B) 18.10.2 -> Master

The failed case is LE_SECSTORE_0003, which got ERROR in WriteRead_Max_FileSize()

See details in: https://issues.sierrawireless.com/browse/LETEST-6130?focusedCommentId=7277073&page=com.atlassian.jira.plugin.system.issuetabpanels:comment-tabpanel#comment-7277073
Further testing found the patches should not have bought in additional issue. The same problem was found also in 21.01.0.rc1 - see LE-15850
Patch test is also needed on ThreadX
Patch test success - see LETEST-6130 (Linux) & LETEST-6131 (ThreadX)

commits.commitMessage:
Kernel crash when tz_GenerateKey is called with keysize = 0

Issue Description:
Internal error happens when tz_GenerateKey is called with keysize = 0

Root Cause:
When the NULL pointer dereference by the function call
"dmac_flush_range()" which will lead to kernel crash in this case.

Key size check is needed in "tz_GenerateKey"

commits.commitMessage:
Fixes connecting to AVC when using IOTKeyStore

Issue:
Device cannot connect to the AVC server when IOT keystore is
enabled because it cannot find credentials. The PA uses SFS paths
to look for credentials that are saved to the EFS, so it's unable
to find them.

Solution:
Convert SFS paths to a generic path that is different between
RC76 and WP products.

Resolves: LE-15788
Change-Id: Ib06c2952a99d722b2e8c047c142f42d6fa232d14
commits.subject: Fixes connecting to AVC when using IOTKeyStore

commits.commitMessage:
SecureStorage optimizations for IoTKeystore encryption

1) Reduce number of calls to IKS API if the data chunk allows
to use "packet" (rather than "streaming") API

2) Keep a cached copy of the most recently used IoT Keystore key,
to reduce numbers of key retrieval operations.

3) Disable SecureStorage quota checking. Currently, before every
write operation, SecStore reads / decrypts all data (of this app)
to calculate current usage and enforce quota. This creates huge
performance drag. The fix is to disable quota (as it is done on
RTOS platforms) until better quota enforcement mechanism is
introduced.

Resolves: LE-15361
Change-Id: Ifb44a0897ed94ffaa22c9bbbe3981d07e7130b6e
commits.subject: SecureStorage optimizations for IoTKeystore encryption

comments.message:
What is the use of this if block?
keyRefCache is set to NULL in line# 101. If I understand this correctly, that means the if block will be never executed as keyRefCache must not be NULL to execute the if block?

keyRefCache is declared "static", which means it's initialized only once, and preserves its value between calls to this function (similar as if it was declared globally, outside the function; only difference being the visibility scope). 
I'll add a comment for clarity.
I've renamed "static" variables to start with Capital letter (as per coding conventions); that should emphasis how they behave.

commits.commitMessage:
Rename key file to avoid crash

- When config tree is enabled for secure storage the old
version is built as well to enable the porting over of old keys to
the trustzone version. It uses a "keys" folder which causes a
conflict with the one here. The "keys" folder is renamed to avoid
the crash.
- Also made large buffers that are being allocated on the stack to
be allocated from a memory pool

Resolves: LE-15406
Change-Id: I16f7c1a97391cbddca0c76e9b66cdd6cdec5c482
commits.subject: Rename key file to avoid crash

comments.message: Wasn't it correctly working on Linux? Was this causing crash only on RC76?

My concern here is the upgrade scenario. Old Legato uses "keys", new Legato uses "keysTz" and won't find the old file. The keys will be re-generated, and the old data (encrypted with old keys) will be unreadable.

Is there a way to resolve the name conflict by some other means (i.e. using directory name different from 'keys')?
In the COMPONENT_INIT I could create the keys file if it doesn't exist. That way I think we could avoid the crash but I'll have to test it

The keys file is included as part the Component http://cgit.legato/Legato/platformAdaptor/tzSwi.git/tree/components/le_pa_secStoreTz/Component.cdef

This ensures that during an upgrade, the keys file content gets ported to the updated app.
bundles: section doesn't work on RTOS -- so I guess you need to create the file if it doesn't exist on RTOS only.
What's the behaviour when the app gets updated? we rely on this mechanism to carry defined files over to the subsequent update.

There's no SOTA on RTOS, only FOTA.  And since on RTOS the code is completely unrelated to the filesystem, I believe on RTOS the FS is not touched on FOTA.  But that may depend on the contents of the CWE?
This is cross-platform code, so Linux upgrade will be impacted.
Understood, this was specifically in response to Enoch's question about upgrade path on RC76.
Two exit labels seem redundant, considering that the pointer is checked for NULL anyway.

commits.commitMessage:
Port IKS-based secStore PA to ThreadX

Port the IKS-based secStore PA to compile on ThreadX by:
 - Use new sfsSecStore version of SFS PA instead of dynamically
   loading the SFS PA when needed, as dynamically loading is not
   supported on RTOS.
 - Use FD le_atomFile API instead of stream API, as file streams
   are not supported on RTOSes
 - Change so PA has dependencies on components it uses, instead of
   the dependencies being the secStore daemon.
 - Conditionally adjusting compiler/linker flags for an RTOS
   environment
 - Resolving warnings reported by RVCT compiler

Resolves: LE-15105
Change-Id: I34543286161064446234b7fc7006d80dccb358a4
commits.subject: Port IKS-based secStore PA to ThreadX

commits.commitMessage:
Add PA for IoT Keystore RSA and ECC algorithms.

Create Platform Adaptor routines for RSA and ECC.

Resolves: LE-14867
Change-Id: I474e2a9f866630c3a16cee4eef5e58b8e4aa2767
commits.subject: Add PA for IoT Keystore RSA and ECC algorithms.

comments.message: It appears that ConvertRc() can return you LE_NOT_FOUND, LE_NO_MEMORY, LE_FORMAT_ERROR as well, which you'l return here.
Same for all those functions below calling ConvertRc().

Function iks_rsaOaep_Encrypt()
(http://cgit.legato/IoTkeystore.git/tree/iotKeyStore/core/inc/iks_rsa.h)
can return the following set of values:

 *      IKS_OK if successful.
 *      IKS_INVALID_REF if the key reference is invalid.
 *      IKS_INVALID_KEY if the key type is invalid.
 *      IKS_OUT_OF_RANGE if either the labelSize or the plaintextSize is too big.
 *      IKS_INVALID_PARAM if plaintextPtr, ciphertextPtr or ciphertextSizePtr is NULL.
 *      IKS_OVERFLOW if the ciphertext buffer is too small.
 *      IKS_INTERNAL_ERROR if there was an internal error.

which translates into the set of LE_ values listed at the lines 1359-1363.
I thought you're returning what ConvertRc() returns you, not iks_rsaOaep_Encrypt(). But possible that some of the others won't ever happen.
Yes, others won't happen, since we know that the native IOT Keystore function (that provides the input for ConvertRc) returns only the abovelisted set of IKS_ return codes.

This is a long list of function arguments. From iksEcc.c to here, this is done; and similarly from apps using le_iks_ecc.api to iksEcc.c. This consumes significant heap memory and can exhaust it on low memory footprints. Can you pass a data structure pointer to embed them inside instead, from iksEcc.c to here?

Interesting point.

From the app using le_iks_ecc.api to SecStore process, we can't optimize it by passing a pointer, since it's IPC. Here (when the data is passed to PA), I suppose we could do it... but I'm not certain which way is better.

The pro I think is saving few dozen bytes of stack for a fraction of a second. The con is somewhat losing consistency with (1) native IKS API (2) other pa_iks API functions in this file (3) how things are usually done in Legato (when passing data to PA).

Indeed, yes stack not heap; I said it wrong but you got it.
From LE to PA, we do pass data structure pointers in some occasions.
Let's defer this to LE-15072. There are few more functions in this file that take long list of parameters, so if we go this route it would make sense to convert them as well.
FYI, I am planning to change this API slightly that should reduce the number of parameters a bit.
Thanks for the heads-up Alex. Do you foresee other changes in the existing APIs? After Legato IKS API goes public (out of experimental state), we become quite constrained in making changes.

Then, data structure pointer passing would be even better for hiding the constituents within when they have significant chances of changes in the future.
If you plan to do this or similar in a follow-up patch/ticket, that's fine.
Should this be validated earlier in le_iks_ecc_Ecies_EncryptPacket() than here?

le_iks_ecc_Ecies_Encrypt() will call either this function, or the (empty) default PA. In latter case, these checks don't make much sense; so I'm not certain that platform-independent code would be better place do do these checks. 

If we still decide to move them all (including functions that are not part of this review) one level up the call stack, then I think it better be done under next work item LE-15072.

commits.commitMessage:
Fix SecStore to enable recovery from corrupted keys file.

1) When the keys file is loaded at the init time, check
the validity of the keys by dry-running encryption.
2) If the key is invalid, recover by deleting the keys file
and re-generating new keys as needed.
3) Fix SetCurrSystem to be able to handle unreadable hash file.
4) Fix TZ PA initialization to be able to init at later point
if the first attempt fails due to invalid key.

Resolves: LE-14705
Change-Id: Ib2f6b2f49293b48e3872fab4d7088c24dfed9e5f
commits.subject: Fix SecStore to enable recovery from corrupted keys file.

commits.commitMessage:
Fix for secStore overflow when reading AV credentials

Restore the output buffer size (that may have changed due to the
unsuccessful read operation) to the correct value before performing
fallback SFS read.

Resolves: LE-13640
Change-Id: Ibf18410a5ffe2364b516bc654cb982ce859fa269
commits.subject: Fix for secStore overflow when reading AV credentials

comments.message: May be a stupid question: Do this fix cover the case when credentials are corrupted (Lame example: https://issues.sierrawireless.com/browse/LE-12711)? Does it cover cases when credentials need to be copied from modem read-only data?

This logic covers the case when the AVMS credential is either absent in the new SecStore, or can't be decrypted (because of the lost TrustZone key). The fallback is to read it from the "old" secure storage, i.e. modem SFS.
This logic won't help in the case when the AVMS credential is readable, but for some reason invalid.

Which one of these cases is LE-12711, I'm not sure.

Hi Nasif, this fix has very small scope, and it only addresses the particular SecStore problem, i.e. the logic of fallback read from the SFS if the read from the new TZ-based SecStore fails. 

How to handle properly the case of credentials being readable but corrupted (by user mistake or other reasons), I guess is a topic for a separate investigation. Same for the bootstrap restoration: I'm not sure at this point, why bootstrap credentials aren't restored on failure...

The reason why I asked the Bootstrap failure issue because I faced this issue and I was stuck there last Friday. The fix you made here may mask out the stuff that I was noticing however, it won't be a proper fix because customer may hit there for a different reason (may not simple upgrade/downgrade or secStore read).

I don't like limiting the fix-scope of an issue to very specific case (in that case same issue will come again and again in various forms and wastes our development and validation effort), rather the fix-scope should be the all known cases of that issue.

If this patch is super urgent, then we may create a bug ticket whose fix revision should be next rc.

Hi Nasif,
I think it's a good idea to create a new ticket for the issue you've encountered, which would describe the exact way to reproduce the problem, and all the symptoms and the relevant logs.

commits.commitMessage:
Fix for secStore API not returning LE_OVERFLOW

Two problems:
1) TZ driver crash on decryption operation, when
the output buffer size is 0;
2) If output buffer size is greater then zero but still
insufficient, LE_FAULT is returned instead of LE_OVERFLOW.
The fix is to change the logic to avoid calling TZ driver with
zero buffer size, and use separately allocated buffer for
encryption/decryption result.

Resolves: LE-13340
Change-Id: I1c5bd683f2d96b5b0f04d0122fe6ca3ea5c200ba
commits.subject: Fix for secStore API not returning LE_OVERFLOW

commits.commitMessage:
Fix for secStore Write() failing after key is re-created.

File with TrustZone keys can be lost for example due to Legato
being temporarily downgraded and then upgraded again to 19.07+.
In this case, the total size calculation is failing, and this
is preventing the Write() operation from succeeding. As a
result, the old data can't be overwritten.

The fix is to make size calculation tolerant to decryption failure.
If the data can't be decrypted, just use the encrypted size
(which is slightly larger) and proceed.

Resolves: LE-13342
Change-Id: Ia64635ae15badbabebd43d4a9531bfa021dc4e93
commits.subject: Fix for secStore Write() failing after key is re-created.

commits.commitMessage:
Fix for "secstore readmeta" command not working.

The problem is that in new TrustZone-based implementation, the meta
file does not exist, and can't be simply copied to the provided path.

The fix is to generate the meta data on demand, and write it to the
provided file path.

Resolves: LE-13343
Change-Id: I9acc0f890da6bcd09369ed5098730d324c152e39

commits.commitMessage:
Fix for: "secstore total" returns error

The problem is, that "GetTotal()" API is not implemented in
the TrustZone-based secure storage. The reason being, the data
is saved on RW flash filesystem, and the cap is not enforced.

The fix is to introduce total secure storage limit of 1Mb;
although it's not enforced, this will allow to return some
meaningful numbers for total space and free space.

Resolves: LE-13169
Change-Id: I2a090286c54da8ada9524241353b192d16545d5f
commits.subject: Fix for: "secstore total" returns error

commits.commitMessage:
Fix TrustZone encryption/decryption failing on WP77

Due to firmware limitation, WP77 TrustZone cannot handle 4k buffer.
The fix:
- reduce the buffer to 2k.
- fix an error in the logic responsible for slicing the chunk
exceeding the max buffer
- use separate buffer for calculating the max decrypted data length,
instead of client-provided pointer.

Resolves: LE-13263 LE-13267
Change-Id: Id4bac8fb0fb7b85021558eed30c0f342e1c68f8f
commits.subject: Fix TrustZone encryption/decryption failing on WP77

comments.message:
Usually we start commit messages with a verb.

So: Fix TrustZone encryption/decryption failing on WP77

That global variable looks pretty bad.

Could we get rid of it and instead rely on GetMaxEncryptedSize() to return the value?

If you want to keep the le_result_t, maybe use a pointer to provide the value, but you could also just return 0 in case of error.

GetMaxEncryptedSize is called only once, on the very first encryption or decryption operation. And then we need to store this value (MaxEncryptedSize) somewhere and just re-use it later, to avoid doing this "test encryption" over and over. Currently it's stored in a global variable.

What would be better option? Encapsulate it as a static within this function?

Sure, as a static variable in the function, and we do the request if the static is 0.

What I don't understand is that:
- Does keyPtr/keySize matter?
  If it does matter, shouldn't we be doing the request every time?
  If it doesn't, why is this a parameter?

Thanks, I'll change it to static var.

We need a key to perform the operation. The client is responsible for obtaining the key (using tz_GenerateKey()) and storing it, on the client's side. So we have no choice but to pass it.

Also, in the case where GetMaxEncryptedSize returns LE_FAULT, we might not mark InitTz as true, but we still continue with a MaxEncryptedSize value of 0.

I'm not entirely sure, but it looks like that would create an infinite loop, since eDataSize would always be 0.

Maybe SendTzRequest fails if eDataSize is 0, but not sure.
do we want to have an ifdef for wp76 and wp77 so we can define 4k?

I would go for the safest choice right now which is 2k everywhere.

The fact that the 2k limit is isolated to wp77 is ambiguous: some issues regarding TZ have been raised on wp76, so I don't think we should differentiate for now.

Also, is it that big in term of performance impact? The data that we are encrypting/decoding should be relatively small, smaller than 2k in most cases, so the overall impact should be limited IMHO.

commits.commitMessage:
Fix tz secure storage faulting on restart

When a system with tz secure storage is deployed, a restart operation
will result in the device restarting until it rolls back.

Resolves: LE-13246
Change-Id: Ie5f26f5a2fa23eac4e7c3e62f95fc76a7016f234
commits.subject: Fix tz secure storage faulting on restart

comments.message:
So I understand we first writing the data to the output buffer, and only then checking whether it's overflown.

We could use two-step process. First encrypt to the temporary buffer, then check if it fits into the destination, then copy from the temporary buffer to the destination.

Same for decryption.
Discussed; since we are passing &eDataSize parameter (remaining length) to the TZ driver, it will actually prevent the overrun of the client's destination buffer. So no extra logic is required.
